dually displaced the indigenous peoples of the Hudson Valley. In The Memory of All Ancient Customs he establishes the surprising extent to which numerically small and militarily weak Indian groups continued to understand the world around them in their own terms, and as often engaged— sometimes violently, sometimes cooperatively—with neighboring peoples to the east (New England Indians) and west (the Iroquois ) as with the Dutch and English colonizers. Even as they fell more and more under the domination of powerful outsiders—Iroquois as well as Dutch and English—the Hudson Valley Indians were resilient, maintaining or adapting features of their traditional diplomatic ties until the moment of their final dispossession during the American Revolutionary War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aIndians of North AmericaxGovernment relationsxHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aIndians of North AmericaxHistoryxColonial period, ca. 1600-1775. 0aIndians of North AmericaxHistoryyColonial period, ca. 1600-1775. 0aIndians of North AmericaxPolitics and governmentx17th centuryxHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aIndians of North AmericaxPolitics and governmentx18th centuryxHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aIndians of North AmericazHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.)xGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericazHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.)xPolitics and governmenty17th century. 0aIndians of North AmericazHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.)xPolitics and governmenty18th century. 4aNative American Studies. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh  anative american colonization, native american populations, indigenous social communication, mahicans, wappingers, esopus indians, american revolution, native interaction, native american culture, new england indians, iroqu